WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.680
Hi there, I'm Isabel. I'm a software engineer at Posit, where I build open-source data science

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:11.040
tools. But today I'm going to be here to talk to you all about the TidyTuesday project,

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:15.760
which is a weekly social data project that's hosted by the data science learning community.

00:00:16.719 --> 00:00:22.559
This is a fantastic project. I have loved it for many years. It's actually how I got started in R

00:00:22.559 --> 00:00:28.559
and Python, being able to explore these different data sets. Every week, the data science learning

00:00:28.559 --> 00:00:35.200
community posts a new data set. This could be anything from squirrel sightings in New York City

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:41.840
to chocolate bar ratings or even Taylor Swift lyrics. It's really a wide variety of data sets,

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:46.560
and it's a great opportunity to see types of data that maybe you wouldn't in your daily life.

00:00:47.279 --> 00:00:52.959
It's also a great way to get involved with real-world data and a real-world data community.

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:58.000
And this comes in because once you've analyzed your data, you've made some sort of

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:04.320
app or dashboard or even just a really cool visualization you want to share with others,

00:01:04.320 --> 00:01:10.320
you can post it on social media with the hashtag TidyTuesday. If you go on your favorite social

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:15.760
media and look this up, you will see probably many, many, many examples of this vibrant community

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:20.800
of people sharing out just cool data things. It's really fun to see what other people have

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:27.279
done with the same data that you saw. At Posit, we have loved the TidyTuesday project for a

00:01:27.279 --> 00:01:32.639
very long time, and it's such a great community. We wanted to find a way to get Python users

00:01:32.639 --> 00:01:38.559
involved to really learn these critical data science skills and explore data in kind of a

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:45.599
fun community-centered way. So we've decided to host a challenge alongside the data set that gets

00:01:45.599 --> 00:01:51.839
released for TidyTuesday. You can solve the TidyTuesday, of course, in R or Python, but every

00:01:51.839 --> 00:01:56.959
week we'll be sharing some sort of Python solution to the challenge we pose to people. I'll show you

00:01:56.959 --> 00:02:02.239
all an example, so let's get started. So I'm in the Positron IDE. We're going to be doing a little

00:02:02.239 --> 00:02:09.839
bit of data analysis for Central Park squirrel sightings. This is a TidyTuesday data set that

00:02:09.839 --> 00:02:18.320
was released in 2023 on May 23rd. I think it's a lot of fun, and I think it'll be a good way to

00:02:18.320 --> 00:02:23.600
show everyone just kind of the beauty of the TidyTuesday world. So we're going to start by

00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:29.360
loading our data in using Pandas. Later on, I'll also be using Matplotlib and Seaborn, so I've

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:37.839
imported those as well. I find the easiest way to load data is by using just the raw URL given by

00:02:37.839 --> 00:02:45.440
GitHub. So I'll get the raw URL, paste it in here, and do pandas read csv to get a data frame.

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:51.039
We can run this cell, and I'm going to look over at this variables pane,

00:02:51.039 --> 00:02:56.479
maybe just peek at the data here. We can collapse these little spark lines

00:02:57.839 --> 00:03:04.960
and see what sort of data is available. This is also on the TidyTuesday website. Each data set

00:03:05.039 --> 00:03:09.520
comes with a data dictionary, so you know what each column is going to be all about,

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:16.800
but we can look for ourselves. So we have x, y, I think that's the latitude and longitude of each

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:25.039
squirrel, unique squirrel ID, things like primary fur color, highlight fur color, some notes,

00:03:25.839 --> 00:03:33.919
see if they've been running, chasing, climbing, eating, foraging, and maybe what sounds they're

00:03:33.919 --> 00:03:40.160
making if their tail is twitching. All right, so we know a little bit about our data,

00:03:41.199 --> 00:03:46.160
and I think there's a lot of missing values, so we're just going to fill those in with unknown

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:50.800
to give us a little bit prettier plot. We're also going to be dropping some columns that have a lot

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:55.119
of missing values that we don't want for our analysis, so I can run this cell as well.

00:03:55.759 --> 00:04:01.759
So the first question I think I'm interested in answering is maybe what color of squirrels are

00:04:01.759 --> 00:04:09.360
sighted the most. So our first plot, we'll maybe explore this. I'll look at it using matplotlib

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:19.440
and seaborn. We'll start by making a matplotlib figure. Then we'll be using a seaborn countplot

00:04:19.519 --> 00:04:26.799
Then we'll be using a seaborn countplot and wanting to think about the primary fur color.

00:04:27.359 --> 00:04:35.200
If we look at maybe all of the different options for what we have, I would think the primary fur

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:41.600
color is more important than the highlights of the squirrel. We also want to add in the order

00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:49.119
so we can see these fur colors in order from maybe greatest to least. So we can see here

00:04:49.119 --> 00:04:55.359
we have a pretty good idea of mostly gray squirrels next to cinnamon, black, or unknown.

00:04:56.880 --> 00:05:01.679
And just for later us, let's add in what question are we trying to answer with this.

00:05:02.559 --> 00:05:07.359
Maybe another question is what are the squirrels doing when they're being sighted?

00:05:07.359 --> 00:05:12.720
So let's make a second chart to see maybe what are the different activities that are occurring.

00:05:13.679 --> 00:05:20.079
We can take a peek at how many activities are being done. Looks like foraging is happening

00:05:20.079 --> 00:05:24.000
the most, but let's throw in a plot as well so we can share this more easily with others.

00:05:25.119 --> 00:05:30.959
All right, so we also have a little bar chart of the different activities that are happening.

00:05:30.959 --> 00:05:36.160
I'm going to add a little bit more pizzazz onto all of these plots and we'll come back to see

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:42.399
what the end result looks like. This looks fantastic. Let's go figure out how to put it on

00:05:42.399 --> 00:05:51.040
Posit Connect Cloud. So now that I have my quarto markdown file created, I pushed it up to GitHub

00:05:51.040 --> 00:05:56.640
so everyone far and wide can see it. My source code is available for others. And this looks

00:05:56.640 --> 00:06:02.559
great. You know, I have all of my Python code, we can see all of my plots, but the one thing is that

00:06:02.559 --> 00:06:07.839
it's not rendered here. And if I want someone to not see the source code, but maybe the beautiful

00:06:07.839 --> 00:06:16.399
plots that I've generated, what I really want is this HTML file or this HTML rendered output

00:06:16.399 --> 00:06:22.000
somewhere available that doesn't quite look like this. I want to see that beautiful webpage that

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:28.239
Quarto creates. So we're going to use Posit's Connect Cloud to render this file and be able

00:06:28.239 --> 00:06:33.920
to share it far and wide with the TidyTuesday community. One thing that I will need before

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:40.079
we publish is a requirements.txt file. This is going to tell Connect Cloud what needs to be

00:06:40.079 --> 00:06:46.399
installed to be able to run my code. So we know that we've used Matplotlib, Pandas, Seaborn,

00:06:46.399 --> 00:06:53.279
and then in order to run Quarto itself, we'll need Jupyter as well. All right. So let's go to

00:06:53.279 --> 00:06:59.040
Connect Cloud. So I was able to just sign in with my GitHub account. It was super easy setup,

00:06:59.600 --> 00:07:06.880
and let's start publishing things. So I know I made a Quarto file, so we'll select our framework

00:07:06.880 --> 00:07:12.640
to be Quarto. It's this TidyTuesday repository. I'm on the main branch, and the primary file

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:18.880
that I would like to be published is this squirrels.qmd. There's some advanced settings

00:07:18.880 --> 00:07:25.440
if you want to change your Python version. 3.11 should be fine, and I'll toggle this setting to

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:33.519
publish on push as well. So let's make this public, and let's publish it. So one thing that's really

00:07:33.519 --> 00:07:39.040
nice about Connect Cloud is number one, it's super fast. You can see we're installing dependencies.

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:44.480
Already done. We're rendering the document. It shouldn't take more than a second,

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:51.600
and we are publishing for everybody to see, and this is all live, and there you go. That was

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:59.119
exactly as long as it took to publish something from a GitHub repository to Posit's Connect Cloud.

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:06.799
I'm able to share this with others. I can copy my link here, post it on LinkedIn or BlueSky or

00:08:06.799 --> 00:08:12.079
wherever you're active, and really connect with other people in the TidyTuesday community,

00:08:12.079 --> 00:08:17.279
maybe show your friends and family all you've learned about Central Park squirrel sightings or

00:08:17.279 --> 00:08:22.720
whatever other datasets are available through TidyTuesday. That has been a very quick example

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:30.399
of what a TidyTuesday dataset looks like and how you might publish an example of your work on Posit

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:36.640
Connect Cloud. We hope you enjoyed this little walkthrough, and hope to see you online on the

00:08:36.719 --> 00:08:42.000
TidyTuesday hashtag. This has been a great community, and it is only because of people

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:47.919
like you who really engage and share the joy of data with others. So thank you so

00:08:47.919 --> 00:08:50.320
much for watching, and we'll see you online.

